{
  "texts": [
    "For any full possibility frame F, rich possibility frame G, and possibility morphism g: F → G, define g:(F b) p → G such that for X ∈ (F b) p, g(X) = g[X], where is the join operation in the complete Boolean lattice underlying the rich frame G. Then: 1. g is a p-morphism; 2. g is the unique possibility morphism from (F b) p to G such that g = g • ζ F, so the following diagram commutes:F (F b) p G g ζ F gProof.",
    "For part 1, we use the fact that since G is rich, the map ζ G: G → (G b) p is an isomorphism by Theorem 5.24.1, and the map (g b) p: (F b) p → (G b) p is a p-morphism by Theorem 5.18.1.",
    "Thus, to show that g is a p-morphism, it suffices to prove that g= ζ -1 G • (g b) p, or equivalently, ζ G • g = (g b) p. On one hand, for each X ∈ (g b) p we have: ζ G (g(X)) = {x ′ ∈ G | x ′ ⊑ G s g(X)} by definition of ζ G = {x ′ ∈ G | x ′ ⊑ G g(X)} since G is rich and hence separative = {x ′ ∈ G | x ′ ⊑ G g[X]} by definition of g.On the other hand, for each X ∈ (g b) p we have:(g b) p (X) = {Y ∈ (G b) p | X ≤ G b g b (Y)} by definition of (•) p = {Y ∈ (G b) p | X ⊆ g -1 [Y]} by definition of (•) b = {Y ∈ (G b) p | X ⊆ g -1 [Y]} because G is full = {Y ∈ (G b) p | g[X] ⊆ Y }.",
    "If Y ∈ (G b) p, then since G is rich and hence principal, Y = {y ′ ∈ G | y ′ ⊑ G y} for some y ∈ G, so g[X] ⊆ Y implies g[X] ⊑ G y, which in turn implies ζ G (g(X)) ⊆ Y.",
    "Thus, ζ G (g(X)) ⊆ (g b) p (X)."
  ]
}